[3]
Date: Fri 15 Mar 2003
From: Tzay-Jinn Chen <wpc94@yahoo.com>
Source: Center for Disease Control, Department of Health, Taiwan, Fri 14
Mar 2003 [edited]


Taiwan: Suspected Atypical Pneumonia Cases
------------------------------------------
The Department of Health, Taiwan, reported a 54-year-old man who had been
hospitalized due to atypical pneumonia on 10 Mar 2003. This Taiwanese
businessman had a business trip in Dong Guan (Guandong), PRC from 5 to 21
Feb 2003 and returned on 21 Feb with flu-like symptom. On 25 Feb 2003,
fever and intermittent diarrhea began, and the symptoms worsened to include
cough and exertional dyspnea on 6 Mar 2003. The businessman was sent to an
emergency room on 8 Mar 2003 and was hospitalized due to bilateral lung
diffused infiltration (revealed by chest radiogram) and elevation of
leukocyte count. 2 days later, he was transferred to the intensive care
unit due to acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS), and artificial
ventilation was administered.

The businessman's wife, a 51-year-old woman who had not traveled abroad,
also developed fever and other flu-like symptoms, slight bloody sputum, and
diarrhea on 7 Mar 2003. Her chest radiogram showed an infiltration lesion
in the left-upper lung compatible with atypical pneumonia.

All necessary samples have been taken for pathogen study and isolation
procedures. The health authorities in Taiwan continue to observe this event
closely.

--
Tzay-Jinn Chen, MD, MPH
Director-General
Center for Disease Control
Department of Health
Taiwan
<wpc94@yahoo.com>

