Source: Hoover's online, Associated Press report, Fri 14 Mar 2003 [edited]
<http://huknews.hoovers.com/fp.asp?layout=displaynews&doc_id=NR20030314140.5_d38d000d0537d7fb>


Hong Kong SAR: Government Says Pneumonia Outbreak Confined to Hospitals
---------------------------------------------------
5 more hospital workers showed symptoms of pneumonia on Friday, bringing
the total to 29 in an outbreak that raised fears of a mystery illness. But
Hong Kong's top health official insisted no epidemic is afoot. "We are not
talking about any outbreak in the community," said Dr. Yeoh Eng-kiong, Hong
Kong's secretary for health, welfare and food. 2 of the hospital workers
were in serious condition but most were stable, officials said.

43 workers from 4 Hong Kong hospitals have fallen ill, and 29 displayed
signs of pneumonia, raising fears that an atypical form of pneumonia that
recently killed 5 people in neighboring Guangdong province had made its way
to this former British colony. Health officials were also trying to see
whether there are any links to a disease that spread through a hospital in
Vietnam, forcing its closure early this week. An American businessman from
Shanghai became ill with atypical pneumonia on a trip to Hanoi and infected
26 workers there before being flown to Hong Kong, where he died Thursday.

The World Health Organization has issued a global alert, but no links have
been confirmed among the disease outbreaks in Hong Kong, mainland China,
and Vietnam. Yeoh told reporters Friday the new cases reported in Hong Kong
were atypical pneumonia caused by influenza or other viruses, instead of
the bacteria that cause regular pneumonia. Yeoh said the territory has not
seen a jump in overall pneumonia cases or atypical cases, but the hospital
workers were vulnerable because they may have treated patients with
atypical pneumonia. Hong Kong gets about 1500 to 2000 cases of pneumonia
each month, with about half of them atypical, Yeoh said, adding that both
types are commonly seen all over the world. Despite such assurances, many
Hong Kong residents are frightened. Most of the pneumonia cases have
occurred in workers at the Prince of Wales Hospital in suburban Shatin,
where residents have been snapping up surgical masks. The American man died
far away in another part of Hong Kong, in a hospital that has not reported
any of its employees ill with pneumonia.

Although just 6 people have died in the outbreaks under investigation, WHO
spokesman Dick Thompson said officials were worried because the disease
spread quickly, and they are not sure what caused it. In Taipei, officials
at Chiang Kai-shek International Airport put up posters and handed out
leaflets warning Taiwanese travelers about the outbreak in Hong Kong and
urging them to be cautious if they go to Hong Kong or mainland China.

[Byline: Min Lee]

